      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5aa94b69a9143116",
      "text": "*This page is the result of a bunch of notes I took while having a conversation with [[David Bovill]] about the opportunity to work with a great Bordeaux-based Indie Hoster called [http://aquilenet.fr Aquilenet] I am a member of.*"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "49b728848dff03c7",
      "text": "# Local indie hosters nowadays:\n-  their members have great human, political, social values\n- they have all the technical skills we need included advanced one, and are very talented people to build a full information and technical infrastructure ofr a federation of peers\n- however according to David they are often somehow stuck in their so-to-say \"teenager imaginary\" somehow (end of 90s, beginning of 2000s)\n\nConsequently, they are still not adopting new powerful technologies like holochain and such for example.\n\nTo take a metaphor: the fact is that they want to host everything, all the services needed for users to communicate with robust free and opensource software (mail, files, apps and sites hosting, files exchange,..)   in their own castle.\nSo taking the example of [[federated wiki]], yes it is true that they can host easily host it on their own server to enable the members of their community to produced a collective documentation.\n\nThough the real power of with fed.wiki is actually that you can host it anywhere.\n\nFor example, see yr DNS server: you have had issues with understanding the ovh and the Netlify DNS management to make them communicate. Indeed, anytime you go to a new castle (or call it a federation)they have their own language but do not necessarily talk easily with each others.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "69acf83dd19a9e17",
      "text": "# The Old Way of Hosting & Deploying:\nHosting servers do everything for you: they host your emails, your site and apps with on an ftp, your domain names, etc..."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d4e86888b264d34d",
      "text": "# The New Way of Hosting & Deploying\n**Hosting and deploying with the command line** (example: digital ocean).\nMeaning you are not tied to their particular interface, culture, language, or financial structure. \n\n\nFor example, if they shut down their servers overnight, you can easily move to another company. How?\n\nThis flexibility is enabled thanks to a specific tool called *Docker*, that lets you deplopy on any server here or there through your local terminal anytime you want to: then you are actually free.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "376d056b10feea66",
      "text": "Technically, it is called:**independant losely coupled servers**.\nFor example, the command line is loosely coupled from one command to another.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "9c03b46f3b475eaa",
      "text": "So from a technological standpoint, what enables you to be free is both the Docker (which is like a virtual machine that simulated a server let's say) + IPFS which is its coupled storage for your own data (meaning you can store your data locally and quite easily have a p2p communication with any other machine in the world).\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "41c9fdf4a16b9001",
      "text": "As a conclusion,\nYou cannot be stuck in a culture anymore,\nAnd you have your own common tools with all the other tribes.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "61756e9a6e427066",
      "text": "# Why do Indie Hosters stay stuck in the past thenas they are full of smart people?\n- because of teenager images\n- Because of the emotional link to the things they built and that took them 3-4 years to build\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c6a473314e9e0dc0",
      "text": "# How to collaborate with them then?\nOvercome resistence with an initial positive project, especially with their younger.\nFor instance, fed.wiki and IPFS, and micro-services (podcasting easily with 100s of other communities around the world)\nCCL: value through conversations with other federations worldwide."
